# 3D Spatial Subclonal Evolution Simulation in HNSCC

This repository contains the simulation code used in the study:
\*\*“Branched evolution and macroevolution-like transitions shape head and neck squamous cell carcinoma across space and stage.”\*\*
The script implements a three-dimensional deme-based spatial tumor evolution model to simulate mutation-driven subclone generation, clonal growth, phylogenetic topology, subclone abundance, and spatial distribution in head and neck squamous cell carcinoma (HNSCC).

## Overview
The model represents tumor growth on a 3D spherical lattice of demes. Each deme has a finite carrying capacity and interacts with its six nearest neighbors. During simulation, cells undergo birth, death, migration, driver mutation, passenger mutation, and stochastic branching. Driver accumulation increases clone fitness through a saturating fitness function. The model also allows transient CIN-like mutational bursts in defined spatial and temporal windows.

## Main Outputs
The script generates:
- Filtered subclone abundance tables
- Subclone growth curves
- Phylogenetic topology trees
- Spatial Z-plane distribution plots
- Diversity metrics including PHI, Shannon index, and Simpson index

## Requirements
Python 3.8+ is recommended.
Required packages:
```bash
pip install numpy pandas matplotlib networkx openpyxl
Optional package:
&#x20; pip install numba
numba is used for optional acceleration. The script can still run without it.

Usage
Edit the output directory in the script:
&#x20; base\_dir = r"C:\subclone\_simulation\_outputs"
Then run:
&#x20; python deme3d\_simulation\_github\_ready.py
To make simulations reproducible, set:
&#x20; SEED\_BASE = 12345
If SEED\_BASE = None, simulations will be stochastic.
Key Parameters

| Parameter                            | Description                                      
| ------------------- ------------------------------------------------ 
| `RUNS`                               | Number of independent simulation runs            
| `t\_max`                             | Maximum simulation time                          
| `C\_deme`                            | Carrying capacity of each deme                   
| `K\_env\_total\_cells`               | Global environmental carrying capacity           
| `p\_d`                               | Driver-event probability per division            
| `PASSENGER\_LAMBDA`                  | Passenger mutation rate per division             
| `DRIVER\_LAMBDA`                     | Driver mutation number per driver event          
| `s\_max`                             | Maximum driver-associated fitness advantage      
| `alpha\_advantage`                   | Diminishing-return coefficient of driver fitness 
| `m`                                  | Migration parameter                              
| `CIN\_ENABLED`                       | Whether to enable CIN-like mutational burst      
| `A`                                  | CIN amplification factor                         


Output Files
For each run, the script creates an independent folder containing:
&#x20; filtered\_clone\_counts\_t\*.xlsx
&#x20; clone\_growth\_curves\_filtered\_t\*.pdf
&#x20; phylogenetic\_tree\_filtered\_t\*.pdf
&#x20; z\_plane\_t\*\_\*.pdf

These files summarize clone abundance, temporal growth, phylogenetic relationships, and spatial subclone distribution.

Notes
This model is intended as a mechanistic simulation framework for studying spatial subclonal diversification and branched evolution in HNSCC. It is not designed to reconstruct the exact evolutionary history of a specific patient tumor, but to explore how mutation, spatial constraint, competition, migration, and transient mutational acceleration may jointly shape tumor evolutionary architecture.



Citation
If using or adapting this code, please cite the associated manuscript:
Branched evolution and macroevolution-like transitions shape head and neck squamous cell carcinoma across space and stage.